<article>
    <h1>De&#xAD;but nov&#xAD;el&#xAD;ists made good</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201101/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-01"><time>2020-11-01</time></a>
        - <span>BOOKS</span>
        - <span role="byline">Olivia Ho&#xD;&#xA;Arts Cor&#xAD;re&#xAD;spon&#xAD;dent olivi&#xAD;aho@sph.com.sg</span>
    </section>

    <p>De­buts rule the roost in this year’s Booker Prize for Fic­tion short­list, with four first-time nov­el­ists in the run­ning for the pres­ti­gious £50,000 (S$88,600) award.</p>
    <p>Many have a fin­ger on the pulse of to­day’s anx­i­eties, such as post­cli­mate cri­sis novel The New Wilder­ness, set in a not-so-dis­tant dystopian fu­ture.</p>
    <p>Sev­eral bring to the fore fraught mother-child re­la­tion­ships, from an artist in In­dia car­ing for a de­men­tia-stricken mother, to a young boy grow­ing up in work­ing­class Scot­land with an al­co­holic mother.</p>
    <p>Who will win the prize come Nov 19? In the sec­ond of a two-part se­ries, The Straits Times re­views the other three books on the short­list and speaks to two of their au­thors.</p>
    <p>This ar­ti­cle in­cludes af­fil­i­ate links. When you buy through af­fil­i­ate links in the ar­ti­cle, we may earn a small com­mis­sion.</p>

